# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: passive-optical-network
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] Passive optical networks are used for the *fibre-to-the-home* or *fibre-to-the-premises* last mile with splitters that connect each central transmitter to many subscribers.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] The 10 Gbit/s shared capacity is the downstream speed broadcast to all users connected to the same PON, and the 2.5 Gbit/s upstream speed uses multiplexing techniques to prevent data frames from interfering with each other.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] Each user has a network device that converts between the optical signals and the signals used in building wiring, such as Ethernet and wired analogue plain old telephone service.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] XGS-PON is a related technology that can deliver upstream and downstream (symmetrical) speeds of up to 10 Gbit/s (gigabits per second), first approved in 2016 as G.9807.1.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] XGS-PON uses time division multiplexing (TDM) and time division multiple access (TDMA).
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] ITU-T G.987 is the standard for 10G-PON.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] Asymmetric 10G-PON is specified as XG-PON1: 10 Gbit/s downstream and 2.5 Gbit/s upstream (nominal line rate of 9.95328 Gbit/s downstream and 2.48832 Gbit/s upstream).
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] Symmetric 10G-PON is also proposed as XG-PON2 with 10 Gbit/s upstream, but would require more expensive burst-mode lasers on optical network terminals (ONTs) to deliver the upstream transmission speed.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] Framing is "G-PON like" but uses different wavelengths from G-PON (using a WDM to separate them) so that G-PON subscribers can be upgraded to 10G-PON incrementally while GPON users continue on the original optical line terminal (OLT).
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] This compares to the IEEE 802.3av standard for 10G-EPON based on Ethernet, which has standardised upstream rates of both 1 Gbit/s and 10 Gbit/s.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] The 10 gigabit PON wavelengths (1577 nm down / 1270 nm up) differ from GPON and EPON (1490 nm down /1310 nm up), allowing it to coexist on the same fibre with either of the gigabit PONs.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] ITU-T Recommendation G.987 is a family that defines this access network standard (referred to as XG-PON).
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] There is also a companion ITU-T standard defining a management and control interface for administering optical network units, referred to by the G.987 recommendations.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] The optical network unit (ONU) supplies network services from the PON to customer premises, connecting customer-premises equipment such as a home gateway or office firewall.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] An optical network terminal (ONT) is an ONU that functions as a demarcation point servicing a single subscriber; e.g., a dwelling or office.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] The ONU receives the downstream data from the Internet or private networks, and also uses time slots allocated by the OLT to send the upstream traffic in burst-mode.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] TDMA time slots prevent collisions with upstream traffic from other users sharing the same physical PON.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] Fibre-to-the-cell site is another emerging application, but has extra synchronisation requirements.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] A specialised cellular backhaul unit (CBU) can provide PON access for cellular networks.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] The OLT (optical line terminal) connects the PON to aggregated backhaul uplinks, allocates time slots for ONUs and ONTs to transmit upstream data, and transmits shared downstream data in broadcast-mode over the PON to users.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] Since 10GPON is designed to coexist with GPON devices, migration to a 10GPON capability could be done by upgrading the OLT and then migrating individual ONUs as needed.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] Normally the OLT is on a card that slots into an OLT chassis at the central office (CO), which uses special uplink cards for Ethernet backhaul to the telecommunications provider's network and internet.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] Uplink cards on access equipment will likely use multiple Ethernet interfaces, although it remains to be seen what uplink speeds manufacturers will offer to support 10GPON access.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] Locating OLTs in outside plant cabinets may be an option for reach extension as a way to minimise the number of central offices covering low population density areas.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] ITU and IEEE are planning for convergence of their specifications at the physical layer in 10G that would allow for the shared chips, optics and hardware platforms, thus driving cost reductions for hardware manufacturers.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] PON optical distribution networks use single-mode optical fibre in the outside plant, optical splitters and optical distribution frames, duplexed so that both upstream and downstream share the same fibre on separate wavelengths.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] 10G-PON is no exception with reach similar to previous standards but supporting a higher split ratio of 128 users per PON, or more using reach extenders/amplifiers.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] Optical splitters creating a point to multipoint topology are also the same technology as those used by other PON systems.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] This means any PON network should be upgradable by changing the ONT and OLT terminals at each end, with no change to the fibre itself unless different connectors are chosen.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] "An Optical Distribution Network (ODN) being installed today will likely need to support four or more generations of PON over its expected 30–40 year life...
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] The fibre should enable maximum flexibility to support any potential new PON technology, be protected with proven, reliable cabling making it easy to install and reliable, and be joined by advanced, low labor and low loss connectivity.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] In an effort to extend the reach with support for 128 subscribers, the standard supports a range of optical budgets from 29 dB to 31 dB.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] A draft update to the standard is expected to further extend this to 33 dB and 35 dB budget classifications.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] A PON with a 35 dB optical budget could span 25 km or more and be shared among 128 subscribers.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] XGS-PON also supports split ratios of up to 1:128.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] Some ONTs can receive a broad range of optical spectrum from 1480 nm to 1580 nm, so making the 10G-PON downstream signal visible to G-PON receivers.
[src:passive-optical-network/10g-pon] As a result, ONTs must block the unwanted downstream signals with a wavelength blocking filter (WBF), a small passive optical device.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] ITU-T **G.984** is the series of standards that define the architecture and operation of gigabit-per-second–capable passive optical network (**GPON**).
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] It is commonly used to implement the link to the customer (the *last kilometre*, or *last mile*) of fiber-to-the-premises (FTTP) services, using a point-to-multipoint design.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] GPON supporting a shared bandwidth of downstream data rates of up to 2.4 Gbit/s and normally upstream rates of up to 1.2 Gbit/s.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] GPON uses passive optical network (PON) is a fiber-optic access architecture in which a single optical fiber from a central location is shared by multiple end users through one or more passive optical splitters in series (cascaded).
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] Unlike traditional point-to-point fiber connections, PON systems distribute optical signals from an optical line terminal (OLT) to many optical network units (ONUs) or optical network terminals (ONTs) without requiring active electronic equipment in the distribution network.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] The absence of powered components between the central location and subscribers reduces infrastructure costs, simplifies maintenance, and increases reliability.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] In a PON architecture, downstream data is broadcast from the optical line terminal (OLT) to all connected optical network units (ONUs), while upstream data is coordinated using time-division multiple access to prevent signal collisions.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] Passive splitters divide optical signals across multiple fibers, typically serving 16 to 64 subscribers from a single fiber feeder.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] The standard specifies transmission convergence layer, physical layer requirements, management protocols, and service encapsulation for high-speed fiber access networks.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] GPON puts requirements on the optical medium and the hardware used to access it, and defines the manner in which Ethernet frames are converted to an optical signal, as well as the parameters of that signal.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] Unlike the EPON standard, which has a much simpler topology, GPON encapsulates Ethernet packets into virtual GPON encapsulation method (GEM) ports, TCONT queues and VLANIDs via OMCI.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] The exact kind of fiber cable and connectors to use is undefined but is broadly using OS2 cable with SC/APC connectors.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] GPON systems require precise timing and clock synchronization to ensure collision-avoidance in upstream transmission in the time-division multiple access (TDMA) from multiple optical network units (ONUs).
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] The optical line terminal (OLT) provides the primary timing reference for the network, distributing timing information through the downstream signal (every 125µs).
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] Optical network units (ONUs) recover the clock from the received downstream data stream and use it to align their upstream transmissions according to time slots (every 125µs) assigned by the dynamic bandwidth allocation mechanism defined in the transmission convergence layer.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] Attenuation classes in GPON define the allowable optical loss budget between the OLT and the ONU, ensuring reliable operation over a passive optical distribution network with varying fiber lengths and splitter configurations.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] The power-levelling mechanism in GPON is used to control the optical transmit power of the ONUs in the upstream direction.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] In a PON, multiple ONUs share the same optical distribution network and transmit bursts of upstream data toward the central OLT.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] Because ONUs may be located at different distances from the OLT and have different optical path losses, the received optical power at the OLT can vary significantly.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] The power-levelling mechanism allows the ONUs transmitter to adjust its launched optical power to compensate for these variations, ensuring that upstream bursts arrive at the OLT within an acceptable dynamic range.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] The mechanism operates by defining different ONUs transmit power levels and corresponding detection thresholds at the central OLT During operation, the central OLT measures the received optical power from each ONU and determines whether the power level falls within the desired operating window.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] If necessary, the OLT sends PLOAM *Change_power_level* message, the ONU adjusts its transmit power to maintain stable reception and prevent receiver overload or insufficient signal levels.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] In contrast to ADSL technology, which deteriorates as the distance between the central office and the household rises, with severe signal loss beyond 3km, all customers may enjoy high-speed network access within the 16km range of a fiber central office.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] The first version of GPON was ratified in 2003.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] Since then, it has been expanded upon and revised several times.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] As of July 2018, G.984.5 is currently being revised.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] The GPON OMCI recommendation G.984.4 draws on G.983.2, which defines the BPON management model.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] However, G.984.4 removed all references to ATM.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] G.988 is a stand-alone OMCI recommendation and supersedes G.984.4 except for GPON specifics that are not defined in G.988.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] Future work on the PON management model is expected to appear only in the GPON space.
[src:passive-optical-network/gigabit-passive-optical-network] Security issues in the G.984 standard series include the possibility of eavesdropping on upstream traffic, replay attacks, PLOAM messages that are not integrity protected and denial of service to other subscribers on the same link.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] An optical communication system uses a transmitter, which encodes a message into an optical signal, a channel, which carries the signal to its destination, and a receiver, which reproduces the message from the received optical signal.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] When electronic equipment is not employed the 'receiver' is a person visually observing and interpreting a signal, which may be either simple (such as the presence of a beacon fire) or complex (such as lights using color codes or flashed in a Morse code sequence).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Modern communication relies on optical networking systems using optical fiber, optical amplifiers, lasers, switches, routers, and other related technologies.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Free-space optical communication use lasers to transmit signals in space, while terrestrial forms are naturally limited by geography and weather.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] This article provides a basic introduction to different forms of optical communication.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Visual techniques such as smoke signals, beacon fires, hydraulic telegraphs, ship flags and semaphore lines were the earliest forms of optical communication.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Hydraulic telegraph semaphores date back to the 4th century BCE Greece.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Distress flares are still used by mariners in emergencies, while lighthouses and navigation lights are used to communicate navigation hazards.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] The heliograph uses a mirror to reflect sunlight to a distant observer.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] When a signaler tilts the mirror to reflect sunlight, the distant observer sees flashes of light that can be used to transmit a prearranged signaling code.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Naval ships often use signal lamps and Morse code in a similar way.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Aircraft pilots often use visual approach slope indicator (VASI) projected light systems to land safely, especially at night.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Military aircraft landing on an aircraft carrier use a similar system to land correctly on a carrier deck.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] The coloured light system communicates the aircraft's height relative to a standard landing glideslope.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] As well, airport control towers still use Aldis lamps to transmit instructions to aircraft whose radios have failed.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] A 'semaphore telegraph', also called a 'semaphore line', 'optical telegraph', 'shutter telegraph chain', 'Chappe telegraph', or 'Napoleonic semaphore', is a system used for conveying information by means of visual signals, using towers with pivoting arms or shutters, also known as blades or paddles.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Information is encoded by the position of the mechanical elements; it is read when the shutter is in a fixed position.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Semaphore lines were a precursor of the electrical telegraph.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] They were far faster than post riders for conveying a message over long distances, but far more expensive and less private than the electrical telegraph lines which would later replace them.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] The maximum distance that a pair of semaphore telegraph stations can bridge is limited by geography, weather and the availability of light; thus, in practical use, most optical telegraphs used lines of relay stations to bridge longer distances.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Each relay station would also require its complement of skilled operator-observers to convey messages back and forth across the line.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] The modern design of semaphores was first foreseen by the British polymath Robert Hooke, who first gave a vivid and comprehensive outline of visual telegraphy in a 1684 submission to the Royal Society.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] His proposal (which was motivated by military concerns following the Battle of Vienna the preceding year) was not put into practice during his lifetime.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] The first operational optical semaphore line arrived in 1792, created by the French engineer Claude Chappe and his brothers, who succeeded in covering France with a network of 556 stations stretching a total distance of 4,800 kilometres (3,000 mi).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] It was used for military and national communications until the 1850s.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Many national services adopted signaling systems different from the Chappe system.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] For example, Britain and Sweden adopted systems of shuttered panels (in contradiction to the Chappe brothers' contention that angled rods are more visible).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] In Spain, the engineer Agustín de Betancourt developed his own system which was adopted by that state.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] This system was considered by many experts in Europe better than Chappe's, even in France.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] These systems were popular in the late 18th to early 19th century but could not compete with the electrical telegraph, and went completely out of service by 1880.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Semaphore flags are the system for conveying information at a distance by means of visual signals with hand-held flags, rods, disks, paddles, or occasionally bare or gloved hands.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Information is encoded by the position of the flags, objects or arms; it is read when they are in a fixed position.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Semaphores were adopted and widely used (with hand-held flags replacing the mechanical arms of shutter semaphores) in the maritime world in the 19th century.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] They are still used during underway replenishment at sea and are acceptable for emergency communication in daylight or, using lighted wands instead of flags, at night.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] The newer flag semaphore system uses two short poles with square flags, which a signaler holds in different positions to convey letters of the alphabet and numbers.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] The transmitter holds one pole in each hand, and extends each arm in one of eight possible directions.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Except for in the rest position, the flags cannot overlap.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] The flags are colored differently based on whether the signals are sent by sea or by land.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] At sea, the flags are colored red and yellow (the Oscar flags), while on land, they are white and blue (the Papa flags).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Flags are not required, they just make the characters more obvious.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Signal lamps (such as Aldis lamps), are visual signaling devices for optical communication (typically using Morse code).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Modern signal lamps are a focused lamp which can produce a pulse of light.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] In large versions this pulse is achieved by opening and closing shutters mounted in front of the lamp, either via a manually operated pressure switch or, in later versions, automatically.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] With hand held lamps, a concave mirror is tilted by a trigger to focus the light into pulses.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] The lamps are usually equipped with some form of optical sight, and are most commonly deployed on naval vessels and also used in airport control towers with coded aviation light signals.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Aviation light signals are used in the case of a radio failure, an aircraft not equipped with a radio, or in the case of a hearing-impaired pilot.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Air traffic controllers have long used signal light guns to direct such aircraft.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] The light gun's lamp has a focused bright beam capable of emitting three different colors: red, white and green.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] These colors may be flashing or steady, and provide different instructions to aircraft in flight or on the ground (for example, "cleared to land" or "cleared for takeoff").
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Pilots can acknowledge the instructions by wiggling their plane's wings, moving their ailerons if they are on the ground, or by flashing their landing or navigation lights during night time.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Only 12 simple standardized instructions are directed at aircraft using signal light guns as the system is not utilized with Morse code.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] A heliograph (Greek: Ἥλιος *helios*, meaning "sun", and γραφειν *graphein*, meaning "write") is a wireless solar telegraph that signals by flashes of sunlight (generally using Morse code) reflected by a mirror.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] The flashes are produced by momentarily pivoting the mirror, or by interrupting the beam with a shutter.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] The heliograph was a simple but effective instrument for instantaneous optical communication over long distances during the late 19th and early 20th century.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Its main uses were in military, surveys and forest protection work.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] They were standard issue in the British and Australian armies until the 1960s, and were used by the Pakistani army as late as 1975.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] In the present day a variety of electronic systems optically transmit and receive information carried by pulses of light.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Fiber-optic communication cables are employed to carry electronic data and telephone traffic.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Free-space optical communications are also used every day in various applications.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Optical fiber is the most common type of channel for optical communications.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] The transmitters in optical fiber links are generally light-emitting diodes (LEDs) or laser diodes.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Infrared light is used more commonly than visible light, because optical fibers transmit infrared wavelengths with less attenuation and dispersion.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] The signal encoding is typically simple intensity modulation, although historically optical phase and frequency modulation have been demonstrated in the lab.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] The need for periodic signal regeneration was largely superseded by the introduction of the erbium-doped fiber amplifier, which extended link distances at significantly lower cost.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] The commercial introduction of dense wavelength-division multiplexing (WDM) in 1996 by Ciena Corp was the real start of optical networking.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] WDM is now the common basis of nearly every high-capacity optical system in the world.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] The first optical communication systems were designed and delivered to the U.S.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Army and Chevron by Optelecom, Inc., the venture co-founded by Gordon Gould, the inventor of the optical amplifier and the laser.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] The photophone (originally given an alternate name, radiophone) is a communication device which allowed for the transmission of speech on a beam of light.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] It was invented jointly by Alexander Graham Bell and his assistant Charles Sumner Tainter on February 19, 1880, at Bell's 1325 'L' Street laboratory in Washington, D.C.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Both were later to become full associates in the Volta Laboratory Association, created and financed by Bell.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] On June 21, 1880, Bell's assistant transmitted a wireless voice telephone message of considerable distance, from the roof of the Franklin School to the window of Bell's laboratory, some 213 meters (about 700 ft) away.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Bell believed the photophone was his most important invention.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] The photophone was a precursor to the fiber-optic communication systems which achieved popular worldwide usage starting in the 1980s.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] The master patent for the photophone (U.S. patent 235,199 *Apparatus for Signalling and Communicating, called Photophone*), was issued in December 1880, many decades before its principles came to have practical applications.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Free-space optics (FSO) systems are employed for 'last mile' telecommunications and can function over distances of several kilometers as long as there is a clear line of sight between the source and the destination, and the optical receiver can reliably decode the transmitted information.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Other free-space systems can provide high-data-rate, long-range links using small, low-mass, low-power-consumption subsystems which make them suitable for communications in space.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Various planned satellite constellations intended to provide global broadband coverage take advantage of these benefits and employ laser communication for inter-satellite links between the several hundred to thousand satellites effectively creating a space-based optical mesh network.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] More generally, transmission of unguided optical signals is known as optical wireless communications (OWC).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-communication] Examples include medium-range visible light communication and short-distance IrDA, using infrared LEDs.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] An **optical fiber**, or **optical fibre**, is a flexible glass or plastic fiber that can transmit light from one end to the other.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Such fibers are widely used in fiber-optic communication, where they permit transmission over longer distances and at higher bandwidths (data transfer rates) than electrical cables.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers are used instead of cables because signals travel along them with less loss and are immune to electromagnetic interference.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers are also used for illumination and imaging, and are often wrapped in bundles so they may be used to carry light into, or images out of confined spaces, as in the case of a fiberscope.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Specially designed fibers are also used for a variety of other applications, such as fiber optic sensors and fiber lasers.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Glass optical fibers are typically made by drawing, while plastic fibers can be made either by drawing or by extrusion.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers typically include a core surrounded by a transparent cladding material with a lower index of refraction.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Light is kept in the core by the phenomenon of total internal reflection which causes the fiber to act as a waveguide.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers that support many propagation paths or transverse modes are called multi-mode fibers, while those that support a single mode are called single-mode fibers (SMF).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Multi-mode fibers generally have a wider core diameter and are used for short-distance communication links and for applications where high power must be transmitted.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Single-mode fibers are used for most communication links longer than 1,050 meters (3,440 ft).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Being able to join optical fibers with low loss is important in fiber optic communication.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] This is more complex than joining electrical wire or cable and involves careful cleaving of the fibers, precise alignment of the fiber cores, and the coupling of these aligned cores.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] For applications that demand a permanent connection a fusion splice is common.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] In this technique, an electric arc is used to melt the ends of the fibers together.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Another common technique is a mechanical splice, where the ends of the fibers are held in contact by mechanical force.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Temporary or semi-permanent connections are made by means of specialized optical fiber connectors.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The field of applied science and engineering concerned with the design and application of optical fibers is known as *fiber optics*.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The term was coined by Indian-American physicist Narinder Singh Kapany.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Daniel Colladon and Jacques Babinet first demonstrated the guiding of light by refraction, the principle that makes fiber optics possible, in Paris in the early 1840s.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] John Tyndall included a demonstration of it in his public lectures in London, 12 years later.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] In the late 19th century, a team of Viennese doctors guided light through bent glass rods to illuminate body cavities.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Practical applications such as close internal illumination during dentistry followed, early in the twentieth century.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Image transmission through tubes was demonstrated independently by the radio experimenter Clarence Hansell and the television pioneer John Logie Baird in the 1920s.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] In the 1930s, Heinrich Lamm showed that one could transmit images through a bundle of unclad optical fibers and used it for internal medical examinations, but his work was largely forgotten.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] In 1953, Dutch scientist Bram van Heel first demonstrated image transmission through bundles of optical fibers with a transparent cladding.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Later that same year, Harold Hopkins and Narinder Singh Kapany at Imperial College in London succeeded in making image-transmitting bundles with over 10,000 fibers, and subsequently achieved image transmission through a 75 cm long bundle which combined several thousand fibers.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The first practical fiber optic semi-flexible gastroscope was patented by Basil Hirschowitz, C.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Curtiss, researchers at the University of Michigan, in 1956.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] In the process of developing the gastroscope, Curtiss produced the first glass-clad fibers; previous optical fibers had relied on air or impractical oils and waxes as the low-index cladding material.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Kapany coined the term *fiber optics* after writing a 1960 article in *Scientific American* that introduced the topic to a wide audience.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] He subsequently wrote the first book about the new field.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The first working fiber-optic data transmission system was demonstrated by German physicist Manfred Börner at Telefunken Research Labs in Ulm in 1965, followed by the first patent application for this technology in 1966.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] In 1968, NASA used fiber optics in the television cameras that were sent to the moon.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] At the time, the use in the cameras was classified *confidential*, and employees handling the cameras had to be supervised by someone with an appropriate security clearance.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Hockham of the British company Standard Telephones and Cables (STC) were the first to promote the idea that the attenuation in optical fibers could be reduced below 20 decibels per kilometer (dB/km), making fibers a practical communication medium, in 1965.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] They proposed that the attenuation in fibers available at the time was caused by impurities that could be removed, rather than by fundamental physical effects such as scattering.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] They correctly and systematically theorized the light-loss properties for optical fiber and pointed out the right material to use for such fibers—silica glass with high purity.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] This discovery earned Kao the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The crucial attenuation limit of 20 dB/km was first achieved in 1970 by researchers Robert D.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Schultz, and Frank Zimar working for American glass maker Corning Glass Works.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] They demonstrated a fiber with 17 dB/km attenuation by doping silica glass with titanium.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] A few years later, they produced a fiber with only 4 dB/km attenuation using germanium dioxide as the core dopant.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] In 1981, General Electric produced fused quartz ingots that could be drawn into strands 25 miles (40 km) long.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Initially, high-quality optical fibers could only be manufactured at two meters per second.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Chemical engineer Thomas Mensah joined Corning in 1983 and increased the speed of manufacture to over 50 meters per second, making optical fiber cables cheaper than traditional copper ones.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] These innovations ushered in the era of optical fiber telecommunication.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The Italian research center CSELT worked with Corning to develop practical optical fiber cables, resulting in the first metropolitan fiber optic cable being deployed in Turin in 1977.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] CSELT also developed an early technique for splicing optical fibers, called Springroove.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation in modern optical cables is far less than in electrical copper cables, leading to long-haul fiber connections with repeater distances of 70–150 kilometers (43–93 mi).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Payne of the University of Southampton and Emmanuel Desurvire at Bell Labs, developed the erbium-doped fiber amplifier, which reduced the cost of long-distance fiber systems by reducing or eliminating optical-electrical-optical repeaters, in 1986 and 1987 respectively.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The emerging field of photonic crystals led to the development in 1991 of photonic-crystal fiber, which guides light by diffraction from a periodic structure, rather than by total internal reflection.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The first photonic crystal fibers became commercially available in 2000.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Photonic crystal fibers can carry higher power than conventional fibers and their wavelength-dependent properties can be manipulated to improve performance.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber is used as a medium for telecommunication and computer networking because it is flexible and can be bundled as cables.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] It is especially advantageous for long-distance communications, because infrared light propagates through the fiber with much lower attenuation compared to electricity in electrical cables.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] This allows long distances to be spanned with few repeaters.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] A data transfer rate of 10 or 40 Gbit/s is typical in deployed systems.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Using wavelength-division multiplexing (WDM) enables each fiber to carry many independent channels, each using a different wavelength of light.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The net data rate (data rate without overhead bytes) per fiber is the per-channel data rate reduced by the forward error correction (FEC) overhead, multiplied by the number of channels (usually up to 80 in commercial dense WDM systems as of 2008).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] For short-distance applications, such as a network in an office building (see fiber to the office), fiber-optic cabling can save space in cable ducts.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] This is because a single fiber can carry much more data than electrical cables such as standard category 5 cable, which typically runs at 100 Mbit/s or 1 Gbit/s speeds.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers are often also used for short-distance connections between devices.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] For example, most high-definition televisions offer a digital audio optical connection.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] This allows the streaming of audio over light, using the S/PDIF protocol over an optical TOSLINK connection.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber optic drones have been used in the Russo-Ukrainian War since March 2024.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] These types of drones are immune to electromagnetic interference and are not affected by electronic warfare systems.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The drones typically carry spools of glass fiber-optic cable ranging from 5 to 30 kilometres (3.1 to 18.6 mi) in length, with experimental configurations reported at up to 65 kilometres (40 mi).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Because the control signals and video feed travel through the glass core at the speed of light without generating radio emissions, the drones cannot be located or disabled by conventional radio-frequency jamming or direction-finding equipment.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Russia's Ushkuynik KVN was among the first mass-produced fiber-optic FPV loitering munitions, deployed from 2024 onward during the Russo-Ukrainian conflict.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] A physical limitation of the technology is cable snagging: if the drone maneuvers sharply through dense terrain, the trailing glass cable can catch on vegetation or structures and snap, immediately ending the mission.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers are used as light guides in medical and other applications where bright light needs to be shone on a target without a clear line-of-sight path.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Many microscopes use fiber-optic light sources to provide intense illumination of samples being studied.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] In some buildings, optical fibers route sunlight from the roof to other parts of the building (see nonimaging optics).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Optical-fiber lamps are used for illumination in decorative applications, including signs, art, toys and artificial Christmas trees.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber is an intrinsic part of the light-transmitting concrete building product LiTraCon.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The bundles are led from exterior/rooftop optical light collectors through small openings or cable ducts and carry the light to where it is needed.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The optical fibers end in hybrid luminaires where the sunlight is joined with electric light, either on demand or to automatically maintain a constant light level even as the available sunlight decreases.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers have many uses in remote sensing.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] In some applications, the fiber itself is the sensor (the fibers channel optical light to a processing device that analyzes changes in the light's characteristics).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] In other cases, fiber is used to connect a sensor to a measurement system.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers can be used as sensors to measure strain, temperature, pressure, and other quantities by modifying a fiber so that the property being measured modulates the intensity, phase, polarization, wavelength, or transit time of light in the fiber.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Sensors that vary the intensity of light are the simplest since only a simple source and detector are required.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] A particularly useful feature of such fiber optic sensors is that they can, if required, provide distributed sensing over distances of up to one meter.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Distributed acoustic sensing is one example of this.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber can also be used in structural health monitoring.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] This type of sensor can detect stresses that may have a lasting impact on structures.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] It is based on the principle of measuring analog attenuation.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] In contrast, highly localized measurements can be provided by integrating miniaturized sensing elements with the tip of the fiber.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] These can be implemented by various micro- and nanofabrication technologies, such that they do not exceed the microscopic boundary of the fiber tip, allowing for such applications as insertion into blood vessels via hypodermic needle.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Extrinsic fiber optic sensors use an optical fiber cable, normally a multi-mode one, to transmit modulated light from either a non-fiber optical sensor—or an electronic sensor connected to an optical transmitter.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] A major benefit of extrinsic sensors is their ability to reach otherwise inaccessible places.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] An example is the measurement of temperature inside jet engines by using a fiber to transmit radiation into a pyrometer outside the engine.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Extrinsic sensors can be used in the same way to measure the internal temperature of electrical transformers, where the extreme electromagnetic fields present make other measurement techniques impossible.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Extrinsic sensors measure vibration, rotation, displacement, velocity, acceleration, torque, and torsion.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] A solid-state version of the gyroscope, using the interference of light, has been developed.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The fiber optic gyroscope (FOG) has no moving parts and exploits the Sagnac effect to detect mechanical rotation.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Common uses for fiber optic sensors include advanced intrusion detection security systems.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The light is transmitted along a fiber optic sensor cable placed on a fence, pipeline, or communication cabling, and the returned signal is monitored and analyzed for disturbances.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] This return signal is digitally processed to detect disturbances and trip an alarm if an intrusion has occurred.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers are widely used as components of optical chemical sensors and optical biosensors.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber is also used in imaging optics.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] A coherent bundle of fibers is used, sometimes along with lenses, for a long, thin imaging device called an endoscope, which is used to view objects through a small hole.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Medical endoscopes are used for minimally invasive exploratory or surgical procedures.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Industrial endoscopes (see fiberscope or borescope) are used for inspecting anything hard to reach, such as jet engine interiors.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber can be used to transmit power using a photovoltaic cell to convert the light into electricity.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] While this method of power transmission is not as efficient as conventional ones, it is especially useful in situations where it is desirable not to have a metallic conductor as in the case of use near MRI machines, which produce strong magnetic fields.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Other examples are for powering electronics in high-powered antenna elements and measurement devices used in high-voltage transmission equipment.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] In spectroscopy, optical fiber bundles transmit light from a spectrometer to a substance that cannot be placed inside the spectrometer itself, in order to analyze its composition.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] A spectrometer analyzes substances by bouncing light off and through them.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] By using fibers, a spectrometer can be used to study objects remotely.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] An optical fiber doped with certain rare-earth elements such as erbium can be used as the gain medium of a fiber laser or optical amplifier.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Rare-earth-doped optical fibers can be used to provide signal amplification by splicing a short section of doped fiber into a regular (undoped) optical fiber line.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The doped fiber is optically pumped with a second laser wavelength that is coupled into the line in addition to the signal wave.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Both wavelengths of light are transmitted through the doped fiber, which transfers energy from the second pump wavelength to the signal wave.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The process that causes the amplification is stimulated emission.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber is also widely exploited as a nonlinear medium.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The glass medium supports a host of nonlinear optical interactions, and the long interaction lengths possible in fiber facilitate a variety of phenomena, which are harnessed for applications and fundamental investigation.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Conversely, fiber nonlinearity can have deleterious effects on optical signals, and measures are often required to minimize such unwanted effects.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers doped with a wavelength shifter collect scintillation light in physics experiments.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber-optic sights for handguns, rifles, and shotguns use pieces of optical fiber to improve the visibility of markings on the sight.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers are used as components in e-textiles.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] This was first done by Harry Wainwright in the 1980s.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] An optical fiber is a cylindrical dielectric waveguide (nonconducting waveguide) that transmits light along its axis through the process of total internal reflection.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The fiber consists of a *core* surrounded by a cladding layer, both of which are made of dielectric materials.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] To confine the optical signal in the core, the refractive index of the core must be greater than that of the cladding.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The boundary between the core and cladding may either be abrupt, in *step-index fiber*, or gradual, in *graded-index fiber*.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Light can be fed into optical fibers using lasers or LEDs.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers are immune to electrical interference as there is no cross-talk between signals in different cables and no pickup of environmental noise.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Information traveling inside the optical fiber is even immune to electromagnetic pulses generated by nuclear devices.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber cables do not conduct electricity, which makes them useful for protecting communications equipment in high voltage environments such as power generation facilities or applications prone to lightning strikes.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The electrical isolation also prevents problems with ground loops.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Because there is no electricity in optical cables that could potentially generate sparks, they can be used in environments where explosive fumes are present.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Wiretapping (in this case, fiber tapping) is more difficult compared to electrical connections.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber cables are not targeted for metal theft.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] In contrast, copper cable systems use large amounts of copper and have been targeted since the 2000s commodities boom.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The refractive index is a way of measuring the speed of light in a material.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Light travels fastest in a vacuum, such as in outer space.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The speed of light in vacuum is about 300,000 kilometers (186,000 miles) per second.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The refractive index of a medium is calculated by dividing the speed of light in vacuum by the speed of light in that medium.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The refractive index of vacuum is therefore 1, by definition.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] A typical single-mode fiber used for telecommunications has a cladding made of pure silica, with an index of 1.444 at 1500 nm, and a core of doped silica with an index around 1.4475.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The larger the index of refraction, the slower light travels in that medium.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] From this information, a simple rule of thumb is that a signal using optical fiber for communication will travel at around 200,000 kilometers per second.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Thus a phone call carried by fiber between Sydney and New York, a 16,000-kilometer distance, means that there is a minimum delay of 80 milliseconds (about ${\tfrac {1}{12}}$ of a second) between when one caller speaks and the other hears.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] When light traveling in an optically dense medium hits a boundary at a steep angle of incidence (larger than the critical angle for the boundary), the light is completely reflected.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] This is called total internal reflection.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] This effect is used in optical fibers to confine light in the core.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Most modern optical fiber is *weakly guiding*, meaning that the difference in refractive index between the core and the cladding is very small (typically less than 1%).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Light travels through the fiber core, bouncing back and forth off the boundary between the core and cladding.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Because the light must strike the boundary with an angle greater than the critical angle, only light that enters the fiber within a certain range of angles can travel down the fiber without leaking out.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] This range of angles is called the acceptance cone of the fiber.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] There is a maximum angle from the fiber axis at which light may enter the fiber so that it will propagate, or travel, in the core of the fiber.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The sine of this maximum angle is the numerical aperture (NA) of the fiber.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber with a larger NA requires less precision to splice and work with than fiber with a smaller NA.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The size of this acceptance cone is a function of the refractive index difference between the fiber's core and cladding.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers with a large core diameter (greater than 10 micrometers) may be analyzed by geometrical optics.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Such fibers are called *multi-mode fibers*, from the electromagnetic analysis (see below).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] In a step-index multi-mode fiber, rays of light are guided along the fiber core by total internal reflection.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Rays that meet the core-cladding boundary at an angle (measured relative to a line normal to the boundary) greater than the critical angle for this boundary, are completely reflected.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The critical angle is determined by the difference in the index of refraction between the core and cladding materials.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Rays that meet the boundary at a low angle are refracted from the core into the cladding where they terminate.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The critical angle determines the acceptance angle of the fiber, often reported as a numerical aperture.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] A high numerical aperture allows light to propagate down the fiber in rays both close to the axis and at various angles, allowing efficient coupling of light into the fiber.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] However, this high numerical aperture increases the amount of dispersion as rays at different angles have different path lengths and therefore take different amounts of time to traverse the fiber.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] In graded-index fiber, the index of refraction in the core decreases continuously between the axis and the cladding.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] This causes light rays to bend smoothly as they approach the cladding, rather than reflecting abruptly from the core-cladding boundary.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The resulting curved paths reduce multi-path dispersion because high-angle rays pass more through the lower-index periphery of the core, rather than the high-index center.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The index profile is chosen to minimize the difference in axial propagation speeds of the various rays in the fiber.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] This ideal index profile is very close to a parabolic relationship between the index and the distance from the axis.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers with a core diameter less than about ten times the wavelength of the propagating light cannot be modeled using geometric optics.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Instead, they must be analyzed as an electromagnetic waveguide structure, according to Maxwell's equations as reduced to the electromagnetic wave equation.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] As an optical waveguide, the fiber supports one or more confined transverse modes by which light can propagate along the fiber.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber supporting only one mode is called *single-mode*.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The waveguide analysis shows that the light energy in the fiber is not completely confined in the core.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Instead, especially in single-mode fibers, a significant fraction of the energy in the bound mode travels in the cladding as an evanescent wave.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The most common type of single-mode fiber has a core diameter of 8–10 micrometers and is designed for use in the near infrared.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Multi-mode fiber, by comparison, is manufactured with core diameters as small as 50 micrometers and as large as hundreds of micrometers.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Some special-purpose optical fiber is constructed with a non-cylindrical core or cladding layer, usually with an elliptical or rectangular cross-section.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] These include polarization-maintaining fiber used in fiber optic sensors and fiber designed to suppress whispering gallery mode propagation.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Photonic-crystal fiber is made with a regular pattern of index variation (often in the form of cylindrical holes that run along the length of the fiber).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Such fiber uses diffraction effects instead of or in addition to total internal reflection, to confine light to the fiber's core.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The properties of the fiber can be tailored to a wide variety of applications.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation in fiber optics, also known as transmission loss, is the reduction in the intensity of the light signal as it travels through the transmission medium.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation coefficients in fiber optics are usually expressed in units of dB/km.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The medium is usually a fiber of silica glass that confines the incident light beam within.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation is an important factor limiting the transmission of a digital signal across large distances.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Thus, much research has gone into both limiting the attenuation and maximizing the amplification of the optical signal.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Single-mode optical fibers can be made with extremely low loss.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Corning's Vascade® EX2500 fiber, a low loss single-mode fiber for telecommunications wavelengths, has a nominal attenuation of 0.148 dB/km at 1550 nm.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] A 10 km length of such fiber transmits nearly 71% of optical energy at 1550 nm.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation in optical fiber is caused primarily by both scattering and absorption.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] In fibers based on fluoride glasses such as ZBLAN, minimum attenuation is limited by impurity absorption.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The vast majority of optical fibers are based on silica glass, where impurity absorption is negligible.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] In silica fibers attenuation is determined by intrinsic mechanisms: Rayleigh scattering and infrared absorption in the glasses through which the light is propagating.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Absorption in silica increases steeply at wavelengths above 1570 nm.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] At wavelengths most useful for telecommunications, Rayleigh scattering is the dominant loss mechanism.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] At 1550 nm attenuation components for a record low loss fiber are given as follows: Rayleigh scattering loss: 0.1200 dB/km, infrared absorption loss: 0.0150 dB/km, impurity absorption loss: 0.0047 dB/km, waveguide imperfection loss: 0.0010 dB/km.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The propagation of light through the core of an optical fiber is based on the total internal reflection of the lightwave, in terms of geometric optics, or guided modes, in terms of electromagnetic waveguide.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] In a typical single mode optical fiber about 75% of light is propagating through the core material, having higher refractive index, and about 25% of light is propagating through the cladding, having lower refractive index.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The interface between the core and cladding glasses is exceptionally smooth and does not give rise to a significant scattering loss or a waveguide imperfection loss.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The scattering loss originates primarily from the Rayleigh scattering in the bulk of the glasses composing the fiber core and cladding.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The scattering of light in optical quality glass fiber is caused by molecular level irregularities (compositional fluctuations) in the glass structure.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Indeed, one emerging school of thought is that glass is simply the limiting case of a polycrystalline solid.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Within this framework, *domains* exhibiting various degrees of short-range order become the building blocks of metals as well as glasses and ceramics.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Distributed both between and within these domains are micro-structural defects that provide the most ideal locations for light scattering.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Scattering depends on the wavelength of the light being scattered and on the size of the scattering centers.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Angular dependence of the light intensity scattered from an optical fiber matched that of Rayleigh scattering, indicating that the scattering centers are much smaller than the wavelength of propagating light.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] It originates from the density fluctuations driven by fictive temperature of the glass, and from the concentration fluctuations of dopants in both the core and the cladding.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Rayleigh scattering coefficient, *R*, can be presented as : $R=R_{\text{d}}+R_{\text{c}}$ where *R*d represents Rayleigh scattering on density fluctuations and *R*c represents Rayleigh scattering on dopant concentration fluctuations.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The only physically significant variable affecting scattering on density fluctuations is the fictive temperature of the glass, lower fictive temperature results in a more homogeneous glass and lower Rayleigh scattering.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Fictive temperature may be dramatically reduced by about 100 wt. ppm of alkali oxide dopant in the fiber core, as well as slower cooling of the fiber during the fiber draw process.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] These approaches are used to produce optical fibers with the lowest attenuation, especially those for submarine telecom cables.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] For small dopant concentrations, *R*c is proportional to *x*(d*n*/d*x*)2, where x is the mole fraction of the dopant in SiO2-based glass and n is the refractive index of the glass.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] When GeO2 dopant is used to increase the refractive index of the fiber core, it increases the concentration fluctuation component of Rayleigh scattering, and attenuation of the fiber.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] This is why the lowest attenuation fibers do not use GeO2 in the core, and use fluorine in the cladding, to reduce the refractive index of the cladding.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] *R*c in pure silica core fiber is proportional to the overlap integral between LP01 mode and fluorine-induced concentration fluctuation component in the cladding.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] In the core of potassium-doped pure silica-core (KPSC) fiber only density fluctuations play a significant role, as the concentrations of K2O, fluorine and chlorine are very low.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The density fluctuations in the core are moderated by lower fictive temperature resulting from potassium doping, and are further reduced by annealing during the fiber draw process.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] This differs from the cladding, where higher fluorine dopant levels and the resulting concentration fluctuations add to the loss.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] In such fibers the light travelling through the core experiences lower scattering and lower attenuation compared to the light propagating through the cladding segment of the fiber.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] At high optical powers, scattering can also be caused by nonlinear optical processes in the fiber.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] In addition to light scattering, attenuation or signal loss can also occur due to selective absorption of specific wavelengths.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The design of any optically transparent device requires the selection of materials based upon knowledge of its properties and limitations.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The crystal structure absorption characteristics observed at the lower frequency regions (mid- to far-IR wavelength range) define the long-wavelength transparency limit of the material.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] They are the result of the interactive coupling between the motions of thermally induced vibrations of the constituent atoms and molecules of the solid lattice and the incident light wave radiation.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Hence, all materials are bounded by limiting regions of absorption caused by atomic and molecular vibrations (bond-stretching) in the far-infrared (>10 μm).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] In other words, the selective absorption of IR light by a particular material occurs because the selected frequency of the light wave matches the frequency (or an integer multiple of the frequency, i.e. harmonic) at which the particles of that material vibrate.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Since different atoms and molecules have different natural frequencies of vibration, they will selectively absorb different frequencies (or portions of the spectrum) of IR light.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Reflection and transmission of light waves occur because the frequencies of the light waves do not match the natural resonant frequencies of vibration of the objects.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] When IR light of these frequencies strikes an object, the energy is either reflected or transmitted.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation over a cable run is significantly increased by the inclusion of connectors and splices.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Connectors typically introduce 0.3 dB per connector on well-polished connectors.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] Splices typically introduce less than 0.2 dB per splice.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] where the dB loss per kilometer is a function of the type of fiber and can be found in the manufacturer's specifications.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] For example, a typical 1550 nm single-mode fiber has a loss of 0.3 dB per kilometer.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p01] The calculated loss budget is used when testing to confirm that the measured loss is within the normal operating parameters.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Glass optical fibers are almost always made from silica, but some other materials, such as fluorozirconate, fluoroaluminate, and chalcogenide glasses as well as crystalline materials like sapphire, are used for longer-wavelength infrared or other specialized applications.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Silica and fluoride glasses usually have refractive indices of about 1.5, but some materials such as the chalcogenides can have indices as high as 3.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Typically the index difference between core and cladding is less than one percent.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Plastic optical fibers (POF) are commonly step-index multi-mode fibers with a core diameter of 0.5 millimeters or larger.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] POF typically have higher attenuation coefficients than glass fibers, 1 dB/m or higher, and this high attenuation limits the range of POF-based systems.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Silica exhibits fairly good optical transmission over a wide range of wavelengths.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] In the near-infrared (near IR) portion of the spectrum, particularly around 1.5 μm, silica can have extremely low absorption and scattering losses of the order of 0.2 dB/km.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Such low losses depend on using ultra-pure silica.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] A high transparency in the 1.4-μm region is achieved by maintaining a low concentration of hydroxyl groups (OH).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Alternatively, a high OH concentration is better for transmission in the ultraviolet (UV) region.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Silica can be drawn into fibers at reasonably high temperatures and has a fairly broad glass transformation range.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] One other advantage is that fusion splicing and cleaving of silica fibers is relatively effective.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Silica fiber also has high mechanical strength against both pulling and even bending, provided that the fiber is not too thick and that the surfaces have been well prepared during processing.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Even simple cleaving of the ends of the fiber can provide nicely flat surfaces with acceptable optical quality.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Silica is also relatively chemically inert.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] In particular, it is not hygroscopic (does not absorb water).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Silica glass can be doped with various materials.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] One purpose of doping is to raise the refractive index (e.g. with germanium dioxide (GeO2) or aluminium oxide (Al2O3)) or to lower it (e.g. with fluorine or boron trioxide (B2O3)).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Doping is also possible with laser-active ions (for example, rare-earth-doped fibers) in order to obtain active fibers to be used, for example, in fiber amplifiers or laser applications.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Both the fiber core and cladding are typically doped, so that the entire assembly (core and cladding) is effectively the same compound (e.g. an aluminosilicate, germanosilicate, phosphosilicate or borosilicate glass).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Particularly for active fibers, pure silica is usually not a very suitable host glass, because it exhibits a low solubility for rare-earth ions.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] This can lead to quenching effects due to the clustering of dopant ions.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Aluminosilicates are much more effective in this respect.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Silica fiber also exhibits a high threshold for optical damage.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] This property ensures a low tendency for laser-induced breakdown.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] This is important for fiber amplifiers when utilized for the amplification of short pulses.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Because of these properties, silica fibers are the material of choice in many optical applications, such as communications (except for very short distances with plastic optical fiber), fiber lasers, fiber amplifiers, and fiber-optic sensors.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Large efforts put forth in the development of various types of silica fibers have further increased the performance of such fibers over other materials.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Fluoride glass is a class of non-oxide optical quality glasses composed of fluorides of various metals.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Because of the low viscosity of these glasses, it is very difficult to completely avoid crystallization while processing it through the glass transition (or drawing the fiber from the melt).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Thus, although heavy metal fluoride glasses (HMFG) exhibit very low optical attenuation, they are not only difficult to manufacture, but are quite fragile, and have poor resistance to moisture and other environmental attacks.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Their best attribute is that they lack the absorption band associated with the hydroxyl (OH) group (3,200–3,600 cm−1; i.e., 2,777–3,125 nm or 2.78–3.13 μm), which is present in nearly all oxide-based glasses.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Such low losses were never realized in practice, and the fragility and high cost of fluoride fibers made them less than ideal as primary candidates.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Fluoride fibers are used in mid-IR spectroscopy, fiber optic sensors, thermometry, and imaging.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Fluoride fibers can be used for guided lightwave transmission in media such as YAG (yttrium aluminium garnet) lasers at 2.9 μm, as required for medical applications (e.g. ophthalmology and dentistry).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] An example of a heavy metal fluoride glass is the ZBLAN glass group, composed of zirconium, barium, lanthanum, aluminium, and sodium fluorides.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Their main technological application is as optical waveguides in both planar and fiber forms.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] They are advantageous especially in the mid-infrared (2,000–5,000 nm) range.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Phosphate glass is a class of optical glasses composed of metaphosphates of various metals.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Instead of the SiO4 tetrahedra in the network solid structure of silicate glasses, the building block for this glass is phosphorus pentoxide (P2O5), which crystallizes in at least four different forms.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The most familiar polymorph is the cagelike structure of P4O10.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Phosphate glasses can be advantageous over silica glasses for optical fibers with a high concentration of doping rare-earth ions.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] A mix of fluoride glass and phosphate glass is fluorophosphate glass.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The chalcogens—the elements in group 16 of the periodic table—particularly sulfur (S), selenium (Se) and tellurium (Te)—react with more electropositive elements, such as silver, to form chalcogenides.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] These are extremely versatile compounds, in that they can be crystalline or amorphous, metallic or semiconducting, and conductors of ions or electrons.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Chalcogenide glass can be used to make fibers for far infrared transmission.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Standard optical fibers are made by first constructing a large-diameter *preform* with a carefully controlled refractive index profile, and then *pulling* the preform to form the long, thin optical fiber.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The preform is commonly made by three chemical vapor deposition methods: *inside vapor deposition*, *outside vapor deposition*, and *vapor axial deposition*.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] With *inside vapor deposition*, the preform starts as a hollow glass tube approximately 40 centimeters (16 in) long, which is placed horizontally and rotated slowly on a lathe.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Gases such as silicon tetrachloride (SiCl4) or germanium tetrachloride (GeCl4) are injected with oxygen in the end of the tube.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The gases are then heated by means of an external hydrogen burner, bringing the temperature of the gas up to 1,900 K (1,600 °C, 3,000 °F), where the tetrachlorides react with oxygen to produce silica or germanium dioxide particles.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] When the reaction conditions are chosen to allow this reaction to occur in the gas phase throughout the tube volume, in contrast to earlier techniques where the reaction occurred only on the glass surface, this technique is called *modified chemical vapor deposition*.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The oxide particles then agglomerate to form large particle chains, which subsequently deposit on the walls of the tube as soot.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The deposition is due to the large difference in temperature between the gas core and the wall causing the gas to push the particles outward in a process known as thermophoresis.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The torch is then traversed up and down the length of the tube to deposit the material evenly.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] After the torch has reached the end of the tube, it is then brought back to the beginning of the tube and the deposited particles are then melted to form a solid layer.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] This process is repeated until a sufficient amount of material has been deposited.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] For each layer the composition can be modified by varying the gas composition, resulting in precise control of the finished fiber's optical properties.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] In outside vapor deposition or vapor axial deposition, the glass is formed by *flame hydrolysis*, a reaction in which silicon tetrachloride and germanium tetrachloride are oxidized by reaction with water in an oxyhydrogen flame.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] In outside vapor deposition, the glass is deposited onto a solid rod, which is removed before further processing.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] In vapor axial deposition, a short *seed rod* is used, and a porous preform, whose length is not limited by the size of the source rod, is built up on its end.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The porous preform is consolidated into a transparent, solid preform by heating to about 1,800 K (1,500 °C, 2,800 °F).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Typical communications fiber uses a circular preform.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] For some applications such as double-clad fibers another form is preferred.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] In fiber lasers based on double-clad fiber, an asymmetric shape improves the filling factor for laser pumping.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Because of the surface tension, the shape is smoothed during the drawing process, and the shape of the resulting fiber does not reproduce the sharp edges of the preform.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Nevertheless, careful polishing of the preform is important, since any defects of the preform surface affect the optical and mechanical properties of the resulting fiber.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The preform, regardless of construction, is placed in a device known as a drawing tower, where the preform tip is heated and the optical fiber is pulled out as a string.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The tension on the fiber can be controlled to maintain the desired fiber thickness.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The light is guided down the core of the fiber by an optical cladding with a lower refractive index that traps light in the core through total internal reflection.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] For some types of fiber, the cladding is made of glass and is drawn along with the core from a preform with radially varying index of refraction.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] For other types of fiber, the cladding is made of plastic and is applied like a coating (see below).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The cladding is coated by a buffer, (not to be confused with an actual buffer tube), that protects it from moisture and physical damage.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] These coatings are UV-cured urethane acrylate composite or polyimide materials applied to the outside of the fiber during the drawing process.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The coatings protect the very delicate strands of glass fiber—about the size of a human hair—and allow it to survive the rigors of manufacturing, proof testing, cabling, and installation.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The buffer coating must be stripped off the fiber for termination or splicing.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Today's glass optical fiber draw processes employ a dual-layer coating approach.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] An inner primary coating is designed to act as a shock absorber to minimize attenuation caused by microbending.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] An outer secondary coating protects the primary coating against mechanical damage and acts as a barrier to lateral forces, and may be colored to differentiate strands in bundled cable constructions.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] These fiber optic coating layers are applied during the fiber draw, at speeds approaching 100 kilometers per hour (60 mph).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Fiber optic coatings are applied using one of two methods: *wet-on-dry* and *wet-on-wet*.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] In wet-on-dry, the fiber passes through a primary coating application, which is then UV cured, then through the secondary coating application, which is subsequently cured.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] In wet-on-wet, the fiber passes through both the primary and secondary coating applications, then goes to UV curing.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The thickness of the coating is taken into account when calculating the stress that the fiber experiences under different bend configurations.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] In a two-point bend configuration, a coated fiber is bent in a U-shape and placed between the grooves of two faceplates, which are brought together until the fiber breaks.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The stress in the fiber in this configuration is given by $\sigma =1.198E{d_{\text{f}} \over d-d_{\text{c}}},$ where d is the distance between the faceplates.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The coefficient 1.198 is a geometric constant associated with this configuration.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Fiber optic coatings protect the glass fibers from scratches that could lead to strength degradation.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The combination of moisture and scratches accelerates the aging and deterioration of fiber strength.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] When fiber is subjected to low stresses over a long period, fiber fatigue can occur.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Over time or in extreme conditions, these factors combine to cause microscopic flaws in the glass fiber to propagate, which can ultimately result in fiber failure.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Three key characteristics of fiber optic waveguides can be affected by environmental conditions: strength, attenuation, and resistance to losses caused by microbending.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] External optical fiber cable jackets and buffer tubes protect glass optical fiber from environmental conditions that can affect the fiber's performance and long-term durability.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] On the inside, coatings ensure the reliability of the signal being carried and help minimize attenuation due to microbending.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] In practical fibers, the cladding is usually coated with a tough resin and features an additional *buffer* layer, which may be further surrounded by a *jacket* layer, usually plastic.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] These layers add strength to the fiber but do not affect its optical properties.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Rigid fiber assemblies sometimes put light-absorbing glass between the fibers, to prevent light that leaks out of one fiber from entering another.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] This reduces crosstalk between the fibers, or reduces flare in fiber bundle imaging applications.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Multi-fiber cable usually uses colored buffers to identify each strand.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Modern cables come in a wide variety of sheathings and armor, designed for applications such as direct burial in trenches, high voltage isolation, dual use as power lines, installation in conduit, lashing to aerial telephone poles, submarine installation, and insertion in paved streets.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Some fiber optic cable versions are reinforced with aramid yarns or glass yarns as an intermediary strength member.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] In commercial terms, usage of the glass yarns are more cost-effective with no loss of mechanical durability.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Glass yarns also protect the cable core against rodents and termites.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Fiber cable can be very flexible, but traditional fiber's loss increases greatly if the fiber is bent with a radius smaller than around 30 mm.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] This creates a problem when the cable is bent around corners.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] *Bendable fibers*, targeted toward easier installation in home environments, have been standardized as ITU-T G.657.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] This type of fiber can be bent with a radius as low as 7.5 mm without adverse impact.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Even more bendable fibers have been developed.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Bendable fiber may also be resistant to fiber hacking, in which the signal in a fiber is surreptitiously monitored by bending the fiber and detecting the leakage.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Another important feature of cable is cable's ability to withstand tension which determines how much force can be applied to the cable during installation.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Optical fibers are connected to terminal equipment by optical fiber connectors.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] These connectors are usually of a standard type such as *FC*, *SC*, *ST*, *LC*, *MTRJ*, *MPO* or *SMA*.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Optical fibers may be connected by connectors typically on a patch panel, or permanently by splicing, that is, joining two fibers together to form a continuous optical waveguide.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The generally accepted splicing method is fusion splicing, which melts the fiber ends together.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] For quicker fastening jobs, a *mechanical splice* is used.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] All splicing techniques involve installing an enclosure that protects the splice.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Fusion splicing is done with a specialized instrument.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The fiber ends are first stripped of their protective polymer coating (as well as the more sturdy outer jacket, if present).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The ends are cleaved with a precision cleaver to make them perpendicular, and are placed into special holders in the fusion splicer.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The splice is usually inspected via a magnified viewing screen to check the cleaves before and fusion after the splice.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The splicer uses small motors to align the end faces together, and emits a small spark between electrodes at the gap to burn off dust and moisture.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Then the splicer generates a larger spark that raises the temperature above the melting point of the glass, fusing the ends permanently.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The location and energy of the spark is carefully controlled so that the molten core and cladding do not mix, and this minimizes optical loss.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] A splice loss estimate is measured by the splicer by directing light through the cladding on one side and measuring the light leaking from the cladding on the other side.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The complexity of this process makes fiber splicing much more difficult than splicing copper wire.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Mechanical fiber splices are designed to be quicker and easier to install, but there is still the need for stripping, careful cleaning, and precision cleaving.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The fiber ends are aligned and held together by a precision sleeve, often using a clear index-matching gel that enhances the transmission of light across the joint.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Mechanical splices typically have a higher optical loss and are less robust than fusion splices, especially if the gel is used.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Fibers are terminated in connectors that hold the fiber end precisely and securely.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] An optical fiber connector is a rigid cylindrical barrel surrounded by a sleeve that holds the barrel in its mating socket.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The mating mechanism can be *push and click*, *turn and latch* (*bayonet mount*), or *screw-in* (*threaded*).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The barrel is typically free to move within the sleeve and may have a key that prevents the barrel and fiber from rotating as the connectors are mated.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] A typical connector is installed by preparing the fiber end and inserting it into the rear of the connector body.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Quick-set adhesive is usually used to hold the fiber securely, and a strain relief is secured to the rear.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Once the adhesive sets, the fiber's end is polished.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Various polish profiles are used, depending on the type of fiber and the application.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The resulting signal strength loss is called *gap loss*.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] For single-mode fiber, fiber ends are typically polished with a slight curvature that makes the mated connectors touch only at their cores.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] This is called a *physical contact* (PC) polish.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The curved surface may be polished at an angle, to make an *angled physical contact (APC)* connection.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Such connections have higher loss than PC connections but greatly reduced back reflection because light that reflects from the angled surface leaks out of the fiber core.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] APC fiber ends have low back reflection even when disconnected.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] In the 1990s, the number of parts per connector, polishing of the fibers, and the need to oven-bake the epoxy in each connector made terminating fiber optic cables difficult.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Today, connector types on the market offer easier, less labor-intensive ways of terminating cables.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Some of the most popular connectors are pre-polished at the factory and include a gel inside the connector.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] A cleave is made at a required length, to get as close to the polished piece already inside the connector.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The gel surrounds the point where the two pieces meet inside the connector for very little light loss.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] For the most demanding installations, factory pre-polished pigtails of sufficient length to reach the first fusion splice enclosure assures good performance and minimizes on-site labor.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] It is often necessary to align an optical fiber with another optical fiber or with an optoelectronic device such as a light-emitting diode, a laser diode, or a modulator.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] This can involve either carefully aligning the fiber and placing it in contact with the device, or can use a lens to allow coupling over an air gap.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Typically the size of the fiber mode is much larger than the size of the mode in a laser diode or a silicon optical chip.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] In this case, a tapered or lensed fiber is used to match the fiber mode field distribution to that of the other element.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The lens on the end of the fiber can be formed using polishing, laser cutting or fusion splicing.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] In a laboratory environment, a bare fiber end is coupled using a fiber launch system, which uses a microscope objective lens to focus the light down to a fine point.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] A precision translation stage (micro-positioning table) is used to move the lens, fiber, or device to allow the coupling efficiency to be optimized.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Fibers with a connector on the end make this process much simpler: the connector is simply plugged into a pre-aligned fiber-optic collimator, which contains a lens that is either accurately positioned to the fiber or is adjustable.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] To achieve the best injection efficiency into a single-mode fiber, the direction, position, size, and divergence of the beam must all be optimized.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] With good optimization, 70 to 90% coupling efficiency can be achieved.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] With properly polished single-mode fibers, the emitted beam has an almost perfect Gaussian shape—even in the far field—if a good lens is used.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The lens needs to be large enough to support the full numerical aperture of the fiber, and must not introduce aberrations in the beam.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] At optical intensities above two megawatts per square centimeter, when a fiber is subjected to a shock or is otherwise suddenly damaged, a *fiber fuse* can occur.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The reflection from the damage vaporizes the fiber immediately before the break, and this new defect remains reflective so that the damage propagates back toward the transmitter at 1–3 meters per second (4–11 km/h, 2–8 mph).
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The open fiber control system, which ensures laser eye safety in the event of a broken fiber, can also effectively halt propagation of the fiber fuse.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] In situations, such as undersea cables, where high power levels might be used without the need for open fiber control, a fiber fuse protection device at the transmitter can break the circuit to minimize damage.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] The refractive index of fibers varies slightly with the frequency of light, and light sources are not perfectly monochromatic.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Chromatic dispersion arises from both the waveguide structure of the fiber and the dispersive properties of the glass itself, with the latter contribution typically being dominant.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] Modulation of the light source to transmit a signal also slightly widens the frequency band of the transmitted light.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] This has the effect that, over long distances and at high modulation speeds, different portions of light can take different times to arrive at the receiver, ultimately making the signal impossible to discern.
[src:passive-optical-network/optical-fiber-p02] This problem can be overcome in several ways, including the use of extra repeaters and the use of a relatively short length of fiber that has the opposite refractive index gradient.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] A **passive optical network** (**PON**) is a fiber-optic telecommunications network that uses only *unpowered* devices to carry signals, as opposed to electronic equipment.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] In practice, PONs are typically used for the *last mile* between Internet service providers (ISP) and their customers.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] In this use, a PON has a point-to-multipoint topology in which an ISP uses a single device to serve many end-user sites using a system such as 10G-PON or GPON.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] In this one-to-many topology, a single fiber serving many sites branches into multiple fibers through a passive splitter, and those fibers can each serve multiple sites through further splitters.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The light from the ISP is divided through the splitters to reach all the customer sites, and light from the customer sites is combined into the single fiber.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] A passive optical network consists of an optical line terminal (OLT) at the service provider's central office (hub), passive (non-power-consuming) optical splitters, and a number of optical network units (ONUs) or optical network terminals (ONTs), which are near end users.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] There may be amplifiers between the OLT and the ONUs.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Several fibers from an OLT can be carried in a single cable.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] A PON reduces the amount of fiber and central office equipment required compared with point-to-point architectures with dedicated connections for every user.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] A passive optical network is a form of fiber-optic access network.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Bandwidth is commonly shared among users of a PON.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] In most cases, downstream signals are broadcast to all premises sharing multiple fibers.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Upstream signals are combined using a multiple access protocol, usually time-division multiple access (TDMA).
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Passive optical networks were first proposed by British Telecommunications in 1987.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Two major standard groups, the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) and the Telecommunication Standardization Sector of the International Telecommunication Union (ITU-T), develop standards along with a number of other industry organizations.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The Society of Cable Telecommunications Engineers (SCTE) also specified radio frequency over glass for carrying signals over a passive optical network.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] CableLabs has developed coherent PON (CPON) that runs at 100 Gbit/s symmetrically and supports split ratios of up to 1:512.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Coherent means it only needs a single wavelength of light to operate.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Starting in 1995, work on fiber to the home architectures was done by the Full Service Access Network (FSAN) working group, formed by major telecommunications service providers and system vendors.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The International Telecommunication Union (ITU) did further work, and standardized on two generations of PON.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The older ITU-T G.983 standard was based on Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM), and has therefore been referred to as APON (ATM PON).
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Further improvements to the original APON standard – as well as the gradual falling out of favor of ATM as a protocol – led to the full, final version of ITU-T G.983 being referred to more often as *broadband* PON, or BPON.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] A typical APON/BPON provides 622 megabits per second (Mbit/s) (OC-12) of downstream bandwidth and 155 Mbit/s (OC-3) of upstream traffic, although the standard accommodates higher rates.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The ITU-T G.984 *Gigabit-capable Passive Optical Networks* (GPON, G-PON) standard, first defined in 2003, represented an increase, compared to BPON, in both the total bandwidth and bandwidth efficiency through the use of larger, variable-length packets.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Again, the standards permit several choices of bit rate, but the industry has converged on 2.488 gigabits per second (Gbit/s) of downstream bandwidth, and 1.244 Gbit/s of upstream bandwidth.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] GPON Encapsulation Method (GEM) allows very efficient packaging of user traffic with frame segmentation.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] By mid-2008, Verizon had installed over 800000 lines.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] British Telecom, BSNL, Saudi Telecom Company, Etisalat, and AT&T were in advanced trials in Britain, India, Saudi Arabia, the UAE, and the US, respectively.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] GPON networks have now been deployed in numerous networks across the globe, and the trends indicate higher growth in GPON than other PON technologies.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] G.987 defined 10G-PON in 2010 with 10 Gbit/s downstream and 2.5 Gbit/s upstream – framing is "G-PON like" and designed to coexist with GPON devices on the same network.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Asymmetrical 50G-PON was approved by the ITU in September 2021, and symmetrical 50G-PON was approved in September 2022.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The first trial of 50G-PON took place in 2024 in Turkey.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] 100G-PON and 200G-PON have been demonstrated.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The first demonstration of 100G-PON in a live network was done in Australia in 2024.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Developed in 2009 by Cable Manufacturing Business to meet SIPRNet requirements of the U.S.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Air Force, secure passive optical network (SPON) integrates gigabit passive optical network (GPON) technology and protective distribution system (PDS).
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Changes to the NSTISSI 7003 requirements for PDS and the mandate by the US federal government for GREEN technologies allowed for the US federal government consideration of the two technologies as an alternative to active Ethernet and encryption devices.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The chief information officer of the United States Department of the Army issued a directive to adopt the technology by fiscal year 2013.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] It is marketed to the US military by companies such as Telos Corporation.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] GPON used in Fiber to the x deployments may face vulnerability to Denial-of-service attack via optical signal injections, unresolved based on current commercially available technologies.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] In 2004, the Ethernet PON (EPON or GEPON) standard 802.3ah-2004 was ratified as part of the Ethernet in the first mile project of the IEEE 802.3.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] EPON is a "short haul" network using Ethernet packets, fiber optic cables, and single protocol layer.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] EPON also uses standard 802.3 Ethernet frames with symmetric 1 gigabit per second upstream and downstream rates.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] EPON is applicable for data-centric networks, as well as full-service voice, data and video networks.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] 10 Gbit/s EPON or 10G-EPON was ratified as an amendment IEEE 802.3av to IEEE 802.3.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The downstream wavelength plan support simultaneous operation of 10 Gbit/s on one wavelength and 1 Gbit/s on a separate wavelength for the operation of IEEE 802.3av and IEEE 802.3ah on the same PON concurrently.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The upstream channel can support simultaneous operation of IEEE 802.3av and 1 Gbit/s 802.3ah simultaneously on a single shared (1310 nm) channel.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] In 2014, there were over 40 million installed EPON ports, making it the most widely deployed PON technology globally.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] EPON is also the foundation for cable operators' business services as part of the DOCSIS Provisioning of EPON (DPoE) specifications.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] 10G EPON is fully compatible with other Ethernet standards and requires no conversion or encapsulation to connect to Ethernet-based networks on either the upstream or downstream end.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] This technology connects seamlessly with any type of IP-based or packetized communications, and, thanks to the ubiquity of Ethernet installations in homes, workplaces, and elsewhere, EPON is generally very inexpensive to implement.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] A PON takes advantage of wavelength-division multiplexing (WDM), using one wavelength for downstream traffic and another for upstream traffic on a single mode fiber (ITU-T G.652, typically OS2).
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] BPON, EPON, GEPON, and GPON have the same basic wavelength plan and use the 1490 nanometer (nm) wavelength for downstream traffic and 1310 nm wavelength for upstream traffic.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] 1550 nm is reserved for optional overlay services, typically RF (analog) video.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] As with bit rate, the standards describe several optical power budgets, most common is 28 dB of loss budget for both BPON and GPON, but products have been announced using less expensive optics as well.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] 28 dB corresponds to about 20 km with a 32-way split.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Forward error correction (FEC) may provide for another 2–3 dB of loss budget on GPON systems.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] As optics improve, the 28 dB budget will likely increase.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Although both the GPON and EPON protocols permit large split ratios (up to 128 subscribers for GPON, up to 32,768 for EPON), in practice most PONs are deployed with a split ratio of 1:64, 1:32 or smaller.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] XGS-PON networks support split ratios of up to 1:128 and 50G-PON supports split ratios of at least 1:256 depending on the OLT.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Splitters may be cascaded, such as in areas with a low population density and thus a low number of subscribers in a given area.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] This can also be done to facilitate reducing the number of subscribers in a PON in the future.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Thus, PONs can have a tree network topology.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] In rural areas, remote OLTs with capacity for only a few users can be used.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Splitters can be made with either planar lightwave circuit (PLC) or fused biconical taper (FBT) technologies: PLC creates optical waveguides in a flat substrate made of silica to split light, and FBT fuses optical fibers together to create a splitter.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] A PON consists of a central office node, called an optical line terminal (OLT), one or more user nodes, called optical network units (ONUs) or optical network terminals (ONTs), and the fibers and splitters between them, called the optical distribution network (ODN).
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] "ONT" is an ITU-T term to describe a single-tenant ONU.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] An ONU is a device that terminates the PON and presents customer service interfaces to the user.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Some ONUs implement a separate subscriber unit to provide services such as telephony, Ethernet data, or video.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] An OLT provides the interface between a PON and a service provider's core network.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The ONT or ONU terminates the PON and presents the native service interfaces to the user.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] A PON is a shared network, in that the OLT sends a single stream of downstream traffic that is seen by all ONUs.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Each ONU reads the content of only those packets that are addressed to it.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Encryption is used to prevent eavesdropping on downstream traffic.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] An OLT can have several ports, and each port can drive a single PON network with split ratios or splitting factors of around 1:32 or 1:64, meaning that for each port on the OLT, up to 32 or 64 ONUs at customer sites can be connected.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Several PON standards can co-exist on the same ODN (optical distribution network) by using different wavelengths.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The OLT is responsible for allocating upstream bandwidth to the ONUs.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Because the optical distribution network (ODN) is shared, ONU upstream transmissions could collide if they were transmitted at random times.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] ONUs can lie at varying distances from the OLT, meaning that the transmission delay from each ONU is unique.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The OLT measures delay and sets a register in each ONU via PLOAM (physical layer operations, administrations and maintenance) messages to equalize its delay with respect to all of the other ONUs on the PON.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Once the delay of all ONUs has been set, the OLT transmits so-called grants to the individual ONUs.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] A grant is permission to use a defined interval of time for upstream transmission.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The grant map is dynamically re-calculated every few milliseconds.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The map allocates bandwidth to all ONUs, such that each ONU receives timely bandwidth for its service needs.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Some services – POTS, for example – require essentially constant upstream bandwidth, and the OLT may provide a fixed bandwidth allocation to each such service that has been provisioned.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] DS1 and some classes of data service may also require constant upstream bit rate.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] But much data traffic, such as browsing web sites, is bursty and highly variable.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Through dynamic bandwidth allocation (DBA), a PON can be oversubscribed for upstream traffic, according to the traffic engineering concepts of statistical multiplexing.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] (Downstream traffic can also be oversubscribed, in the same way that any LAN can be oversubscribed.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] In GPON there are two forms of DBA, status-reporting (SR) and non-status reporting (NSR).
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] In NSR DBA, the OLT continuously allocates a small amount of extra bandwidth to each ONU.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] If the ONU has no traffic to send, it transmits idle frames during its excess allocation.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] If the OLT observes that a given ONU is not sending idle frames, it increases the bandwidth allocation to that ONU.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Once the ONU's burst has been transferred, the OLT observes a large number of idle frames from the given ONU, and reduces its allocation accordingly.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] NSR DBA has the advantage that it imposes no requirements on the ONU, and the disadvantage that there is no way for the OLT to know how best to assign bandwidth across several ONUs that need more.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] In SR DBA, the OLT polls ONUs for their backlogs.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] A given ONU may have several so-called transmission containers (T-CONTs), each with its own priority or traffic class.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The ONU reports each T-CONT separately to the OLT.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The report message contains a logarithmic measure of the backlog in the T-CONT queue.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] By knowledge of the service level agreement for each T-CONT across the entire PON, as well as the size of each T-CONT's backlog, the OLT can optimize allocation of the spare bandwidth on the PON.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] EPON systems use a DBA mechanism equivalent to GPON's SR DBA solution.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The OLT polls ONUs for their queue status and grants bandwidth using the MPCP GATE message, while ONUs report their status using the MPCP REPORT message.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] For TDM-PON, a passive optical splitter is used in the optical distribution network.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] In the upstream direction, each ONU (optical network units) or ONT (optical network terminal) burst transmits for an assigned time-slot (multiplexed in the time domain).
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] In this way, the OLT is receiving signals from only one ONU or ONT at any point in time.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] In the downstream direction, the OLT (usually) continuously transmits (or may burst transmit).
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] ONUs or ONTs see their own data through the address labels embedded in the signal.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] APON/BPON, EPON and GPON have been widely deployed.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] In November 2014, EPON had approximately 40 million deployed ports and ranks first in deployments.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] As of 2015, GPON (gigabit) had a smaller market share, but is anticipated to reach $10.5 billion US dollars by 2020.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] XGS-PON (10 gigabit) is popular among fiber ISPs in the US as of 2022.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] In short it implements the DOCSIS Operations Administration Maintenance and Provisioning (OAMP) functionality on existing EPON equipment.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] It makes the EPON OLT look and act like a DOCSIS Cable Modem Termination Systems (CMTS) platform (which is called a DPoE System in DPoE terminology).
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] In addition to offering the same IP service capabilities as a CMTS, DPoE supports Metro Ethernet Forum (MEF) 9 and 14 services for the delivery of Ethernet services for business customers.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Comcast Xfinity and Charter Spectrum use 10G-EPON with DPoE in newly deployed areas, including new construction and rural expansion.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Radio frequency over glass (RFoG) is a type of passive optical network that transports RF signals that were formerly transported over copper (principally over a hybrid fiber-coaxial cable) over PON.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] In the forward direction RFoG is either a stand-alone P2MP system or an optical overlay for existing PON such as GEPON/EPON.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The overlay for RFoG is based on wavelength-division multiplexing (WDM)—the passive combination of wavelengths on a single strand of glass.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Reverse RF support is provided by transporting the upstream or return RF onto a separate wavelength from the PON return wavelength.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The Society of Cable and Telecommunications Engineers (SCTE) Interface Practices Subcommittee (IPS) Work Group 5, is currently working on IPS 910 RF over Glass.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] RFoG offers backwards compatibility with existing RF modulation technology, but offers no additional bandwidth for RF based services.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Although not yet completed, the RFoG standard is actually a collection of standardized options which are not compatible with each other (they cannot be mixed on the same PON).
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Some of the standards may interoperate with other PONs, others may not.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] It offers a means to support RF technologies in locations where only fiber is available or where copper is not permitted or feasible.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] This technology is targeted towards Cable TV operators and their existing HFC networks, but is also used by Verizon, Frontier Communications and Ziply Fiber to deliver pay TV services over fiber despite these companies never having owned or deployed a HFC network.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Wavelength-Division Multiplexing PON (WDM-PON) is a non-standard type of passive optical networking that is being developed by some companies.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The multiple wavelengths of a WDM-PON can be used to separate Optical Network Units (ONUs) into several virtual PONs co-existing on the same physical infrastructure.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Alternatively the wavelengths can be used collectively through statistical multiplexing to provide efficient wavelength utilization and lower delays experienced by the ONUs.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] There is no common standard for WDM-PON nor any unanimously agreed upon definition of the term.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] By some definitions WDM-PON is a dedicated wavelength for each ONU.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Other more liberal definitions suggest the use of more than one wavelength in any one direction on a PON is WDM-PON.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] It is difficult to point to an un-biased list of WDM-PON vendors when there is no such unanimous definition.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] PONs provide higher bandwidth than traditional copper based access networks.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] WDM-PON has better privacy and better scalability because of each ONU only receives its own wavelength.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Time- and wavelength-division multiplexed passive optical network (TWDM-PON) is a primary solution for the next-generation passive optical network stage 2 (NG-PON2) by the full service access network (FSAN) in April 2012.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] TWDM-PON coexists with commercially deployed Gigabit PON (G-PON) and 10 Gigabit PON (XG-PON) systems.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] While G-PON, XG-PON, and XGS-PON only support one wavelength per direction, NG-PON supports 4 or 8 wavelengths per direction, and 10 Gbit/s per wavelength for up to 80 Gbit/s of downstream and upstream bandwidth.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The concept of the Long-Reach Optical Access Network (LROAN) is to replace the optical/electrical/optical conversion that takes place at the local exchange with a continuous optical path that extends from the customer to the core of the network.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Work by Davey and Payne at BT showed that significant cost savings could be made by reducing the electronic equipment and real-estate required at the local exchange or wire center.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] A proof of concept demonstrator showed that it was possible to serve 1024 users at 10 Gbit/s with 100 km reach.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] This technology has sometimes been termed Long-Reach PON, however, many argue that the term PON is no longer applicable as, in most instances, only the distribution remains passive.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Due to the topology of PON, the transmission modes for downstream (that is, from OLT to ONU) and upstream (that is, from ONU to OLT) are different.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] For the downstream transmission, the OLT broadcasts optical signal to all the ONUs in continuous mode (CM), that is, the downstream channel always has optical data signal.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] However, in the upstream channel, ONUs can not transmit optical data signal in CM.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Use of CM would result in all of the signals transmitted from the ONUs converging (with attenuation) into one fiber by the power splitter (serving as power coupler), and overlapping.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] To solve this problem, burst mode (BM) transmission is adopted for upstream channel.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The given ONU only transmits optical packet when it is allocated a time slot and it needs to transmit, and all the ONUs share the upstream channel in the time-division multiplexing (TDM) mode.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The phases of the BM optical packets received by the OLT are different from packet to packet, since the ONUs are not synchronized to transmit optical packet in the same phase, and the distance between OLT and given ONU are random.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Since the distance between the OLT and ONUs are not uniform, the optical packets received by the OLT may have different amplitudes.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] In order to compensate the phase variation and amplitude variation in a short time (for example within 40 ns for GPON), burst mode clock and data recovery (BM-CDR) and burst mode amplifier (for example burst mode TIA) need to be employed, respectively.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Furthermore, the BM transmission mode requires the transmitter to work in burst mode.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Such a burst mode transmitter is able to turn on and off in short time.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The above three kinds of circuitries in PON are quite different from their counterparts in the point-to-point continuous mode optical communication link.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Passive optical networks do not use electrically powered components to split the signal.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Instead, the signal is distributed using beam splitters.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Each splitter typically splits the signal from a single fiber into 16, 32, or up to 256 fibers, depending on the manufacturer, and several splitters can be aggregated in a single cabinet.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] A beam splitter cannot provide any switching or buffering capabilities and does not use any power supply; the resulting connection is called a point-to-multipoint link.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] For such a connection, the optical network terminals on the customer's end must perform some special functions which would not otherwise be required.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] For example, due to the absence of switching, each signal leaving the central office must be broadcast to all users served by that splitter (including to those for whom the signal is not intended).
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] It is therefore up to the optical network terminal to filter out any signals intended for other customers.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] In addition, since splitters have no buffering, each individual optical network terminal must be coordinated in a multiplexing scheme to prevent signals sent by customers from colliding with each other.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Two types of multiplexing are possible for achieving this: wavelength-division multiplexing and time-division multiplexing.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] With wavelength-division multiplexing, each customer transmits their signal using a unique wavelength.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] With time-division multiplexing (TDM), the customers "take turns" transmitting information.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] TDM equipment has been on the market longest.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Because there is no single definition of "WDM-PON" equipment, various vendors claim to have released the 'first' WDM-PON equipment, but there is no consensus on which product was the 'first' WDM-PON product to market.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Passive optical networks have both advantages and disadvantages over active networks.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] They avoid the complexities involved in keeping electronic equipment operating outdoors.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] They also allow for analog broadcasts, which can simplify the delivery of analog television.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] However, because each signal must be pushed out to *everyone* served by the splitter (rather than to just a single switching device), the central office must be equipped with a particularly powerful piece of transmitting equipment called an optical line terminal (OLT).
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Optical distribution networks can also be designed in a point-to-point "homerun" topology where splitters and/or active networking are all located at the central office, allowing users to be patched into whichever network is required from the optical distribution frame.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The drivers behind the modern passive optical network are high reliability, low cost, and passive functionality.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Single-mode, passive optical components include branching devices such as Wavelength-Division Multiplexer/Demultiplexers (WDMs), isolators, circulators, and filters.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Proposed requirements for these components were published in 2010 by Telcordia Technologies.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] The broad variety of passive optical components applications include multichannel transmission, distribution, optical taps for monitoring, pump combiners for fiber amplifiers, bit-rate limiters, optical connects, route diversity, polarization diversity, interferometers, and coherent communication.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] WDMs are optical components in which power is split or combined based on the wavelength composition of the optical signal.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] *Dense Wavelength-Division Multiplexers (DWDMs)* are optical components that split power over at least four wavelengths.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] *Wavelength insensitive couplers* are passive optical components in which power is split or combined independently of the wavelength composition of the optical signal.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] A given component may combine and divide optical signals simultaneously, as in bidirectional (duplex) transmission over a single fiber.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Passive optical components are data format transparent, combining and dividing optical power in some predetermined ratio (*coupling ratio*) regardless of the information content of the signals.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] WDMs can be thought of as *wavelength* splitters and combiners.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Wavelength insensitive couplers can be thought of as *power* splitters and combiners.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] An optical *isolator* is a two-port passive component that allows light (in a given wavelength range) to pass through with low attenuation in one direction, while isolating (providing a high attenuation for) light propagating in the reverse direction.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Isolators are used as both integral and in-line components in laser diode modules and optical amplifiers, and to reduce noise caused by multi-path reflection in high-bitrate and analog transmission systems.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] An optical *circulator* operates in a similar way to an optical isolator, except that the reverse propagating lightwave is directed to a third port for output, instead of being lost.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] An optical circulator can be used for bidirectional transmission, as a type of branching component that distributes (and isolates) optical power among fibers, based on the direction of the lightwave propagation.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] A fiber optic *filter* is a component with two or more ports that provides wavelength sensitive loss, isolation and/or return loss.
[src:passive-optical-network/passive-optical-network] Fiber optic filters are in-line, wavelength selective, components that allow a specific range of wavelengths to pass through (or reflect) with low attenuation for classification of filter types.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] In fiber-optic communications, **wavelength-division multiplexing** (**WDM**) is a technology which multiplexes a number of optical carrier signals onto a single optical fiber by using different wavelengths (i.e., colors) of laser light.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] This technique enables bidirectional communications over a single strand of fiber (also called **wavelength-division duplexing**) as well as multiplication of capacity.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The term WDM is commonly applied to an optical carrier, which is typically described by its wavelength, whereas frequency-division multiplexing typically applies to a radio carrier, more often described by frequency.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] This is purely conventional because wavelength and frequency communicate the same information.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Specifically, frequency (in Hertz, which is cycles per second) multiplied by wavelength (the physical length of one cycle) equals the velocity of the carrier wave.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] In a vacuum, this is the speed of light (usually denoted by the lowercase letter, c).
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] In glass fiber, velocity is substantially slower - usually about 0.7 times c.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The data rate in practical systems is a fraction of the carrier frequency.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] A WDM system uses a multiplexer at the transmitter to join the several signals together and a demultiplexer at the receiver to split them apart.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] With the right type of fiber, it is possible to have a device that does both simultaneously and can function as an optical add-drop multiplexer.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The optical filtering devices used have conventionally been etalons (stable solid-state single-frequency Fabry–Pérot interferometers in the form of thin-film-coated optical glass).
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] As there are three different WDM types, whereof one is called *WDM*, the notation *xWDM* is normally used when discussing the technology as such.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The concept was first published in 1970 by Delange, and by 1980 WDM systems were being realized in the laboratory.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The first WDM systems combined only two signals.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Modern systems can handle 160 signals and can thus expand a basic 100 Gbit/s system over a single fiber pair to over 16 Tbit/s.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] WDM systems are popular with telecommunications companies because they allow them to expand the capacity of the network without laying more fiber.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] By using WDM and optical amplifiers, they can accommodate several generations of technology development in their optical infrastructure without having to overhaul the backbone network.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The capacity of a given link can be expanded simply by upgrading the multiplexers and demultiplexers at each end.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] This is often done by the use of optical-to-electrical-to-optical (O/E/O) translation at the very edge of the transport network, thus permitting interoperation with existing equipment with optical interfaces.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Most WDM systems operate on single-mode optical fiber cables which have a core diameter of 9 μm.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Certain forms of WDM can also be used in multi-mode optical fiber cables (also known as premises cables) which have core diameters of 50 or 62.5 μm.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Early WDM systems were expensive and complicated to run.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] However, recent standardization and a better understanding of the dynamics of WDM systems have made WDM less expensive to deploy.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Optical receivers, in contrast to laser sources, tend to be wideband devices.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Therefore, the demultiplexer must provide the wavelength selectivity of the receiver in the WDM system.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] WDM systems are divided into three different wavelength patterns: **normal** (WDM), **coarse** (CWDM) and **dense** (DWDM).
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Normal WDM (sometimes called BWDM) uses the two normal wavelengths 1310 and 1550 nm on one fiber.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Coarse WDM provides up to 16 channels across multiple transmission windows of silica fibers.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] *Dense WDM* (DWDM) uses the C-Band (1530 nm-1565 nm) transmission window but with denser channel spacing.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Channel plans vary, but a typical DWDM system would use 40 channels at 100 GHz spacing or 80 channels with 50 GHz spacing.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Some technologies are capable of 12.5 GHz spacing (sometimes called ultra-dense WDM).
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] New amplification options (Raman amplification) enable the extension of the usable wavelengths to the L-band (1565–1625 nm), more or less doubling these numbers.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Coarse wavelength-division multiplexing (CWDM), in contrast to DWDM, uses increased channel spacing to allow less sophisticated and thus cheaper transceiver designs.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] To provide 16 channels on a single fiber, CWDM uses the entire frequency band spanning the second and third transmission windows (1310/1550 nm respectively) including the critical frequencies where OH scattering may occur.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] OH-free silica fibers are recommended if the wavelengths between the second and third transmission windows are to be used.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Avoiding this region, the channels 47, 49, 51, 53, 55, 57, 59, 61 remain and these are the most commonly used.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] With OS2 fibers the water peak problem is overcome, and all possible 18 channels can be used.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] WDM, CWDM and DWDM are based on the same concept of using multiple wavelengths of light on a single fiber but differ in the spacing of the wavelengths, number of channels, and the ability to amplify the multiplexed signals in the optical space.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Erbium-doped optical fiber amplifiers (EDFAs) provide an efficient wideband amplification for the C-band, Raman amplification adds a mechanism for amplification in the L-band.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] For CWDM, wideband optical amplification is not available, limiting the optical spans to several tens of kilometers.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Originally, the term *coarse wavelength-division multiplexing* (CWDM) was fairly generic and described a number of different channel configurations.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] In general, the choice of channel spacings and frequency in these configurations precluded the use of EDFAs.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Prior to the relatively recent ITU standardization of the term, one common definition for CWDM was two or more signals multiplexed onto a single fiber, with one signal in the 1550 nm band and the other in the 1310 nm band.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] In 2002, the ITU standardized a channel spacing grid for CWDM (ITU-T G.694.2) using the wavelengths from 1270 nm through 1610 nm with a channel spacing of 20 nm.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] ITU G.694.2 was revised in 2003 to shift the channel centers by 1 nm so, strictly speaking, the center wavelengths are 1271 to 1611 nm.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Many CWDM wavelengths below 1470 nm are considered unusable on older G.652 specification fibers, due to the increased attenuation in the 1270–1470 nm bands.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Newer fibers which conform to the G.652.C and G.652.D standards, such as Corning SMF-28e and Samsung Widepass, nearly eliminate the water-related attenuation peak at 1383 nm and allow for full operation of all 18 ITU CWDM channels in metropolitan networks.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The main characteristic of the recent ITU CWDM standard is that the signals are not spaced appropriately for amplification by EDFAs.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] This limits the total CWDM optical span to somewhere near 60 km for a 2.5 Gbit/s signal, suitable for use in metropolitan applications.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The relaxed optical frequency stabilization requirements allow the associated costs of CWDM to approach those of non-WDM optical components.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] CWDM is being used in cable television networks, where different wavelengths are used for the *downstream* and *upstream* signals.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] In these systems, the wavelengths used are often widely separated.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] For example, the downstream signal might be at 1310 nm while the upstream signal is at 1550 nm.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The 10GBASE-LX4 10 Gbit/s physical layer standard is an example of a CWDM system in which four wavelengths near 1310 nm, each carrying a 3.125 Gbit/s data stream, are used to carry 10 Gbit/s of aggregate data.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Passive CWDM is an implementation of CWDM that uses no electrical power.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] It separates the wavelengths using passive optical components such as bandpass filters and prisms.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Many manufacturers are promoting passive CWDM to deploy fiber to the home.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] An **intermediate line repeater** is placed approximately every 80–100 km to compensate for the loss of optical power as the signal travels along the fiber.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The 'multi-wavelength optical signal' is amplified by an EDFA, which usually consists of several amplifier stages.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] An **intermediate optical terminal**, or **optical add-drop multiplexer (OADM)**.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] This is a remote amplification site that amplifies the multi-wavelength signal that may have traversed up to 140 km or more before reaching the remote site.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Optical diagnostics and telemetry are often extracted or inserted at such a site to allow for localization of any fiber breaks or signal impairments.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] In more sophisticated systems (which are no longer point-to-point), several signals out of the multi-wavelength optical signal may be removed and dropped locally.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] At the remote site, the terminal de-multiplexer consisting of an optical de-multiplexer and one or more wavelength-converting transponders separates the multi-wavelength optical signal back into individual data signals and outputs them on separate fibers for client-layer systems (such as SONET/SDH).
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Originally, this de-multiplexing was performed entirely passively, except for some telemetry, as most SONET systems can receive 1,550 nm signals.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] However, in order to allow for transmission to remote client-layer systems (and to allow for digital domain signal integrity determination) such de-multiplexed signals are usually sent to O/E/O output transponders prior to being relayed to their client-layer systems.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Often, the functionality of the output transponder has been integrated into that of the input transponder, so that most commercial systems have transponders that support bi-directional interfaces on both their 1,550 nm (i.e., internal) side, and external (i.e., client-facing) side.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Transponders in some systems supporting 40 GHz nominal operation may also perform forward error correction (FEC) via digital wrapper technology, as described in the ITU-T G.709 standard.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] This is data channel that uses an additional wavelength usually outside the EDFA amplification band (at 1,510 nm, 1,620 nm, 1,310 nm or another proprietary wavelength).
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The OSC carries information about the multi-wavelength optical signal as well as remote conditions at the optical terminal or EDFA site.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] It is also normally used for remote software upgrades and user (i.e., network operator) Network Management information.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] It is the multi-wavelength analog to SONET's DCC (or supervisory channel).
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] ITU standards suggest that the OSC should utilize an OC-3 signal structure, though some vendors have opted to use Fast Ethernet or another signal format.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Unlike the 1550 nm multi-wavelength signal containing client data, the OSC is always terminated at intermediate amplifier sites, where it receives local information before re-transmission.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The introduction of the ITU-T G.694.1 frequency grid in 2002 has made it easier to integrate WDM with older but more standard SONET/SDH systems.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] WDM wavelengths are positioned in a grid having exactly 100 GHz (about 0.8 nm) spacing in optical frequency, with a reference frequency fixed at 193.10 THz (1,552.52 nm).
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The main grid is placed inside the optical fiber amplifier bandwidth, but can be extended to wider bandwidths.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The first commercial deployment of DWDM was made by Ciena Corporation on the Sprint network in June 1996.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Today's DWDM systems use 50 GHz or even 25 GHz channel spacing for up to 160 channel operation.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] DWDM systems have to maintain more stable wavelength or frequency than those needed for CWDM because of the closer spacing of the wavelengths.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Precision temperature control of the laser transmitter is required in DWDM systems to prevent drift off a very narrow frequency window of the order of a few GHz.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] These factors of smaller volume and higher performance result in DWDM systems typically being more expensive than CWDM.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Recent innovations in DWDM transport systems include pluggable and software-tunable transceiver modules capable of operating on 40 or 80 channels.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] This dramatically reduces the need for discrete spare pluggable modules, when a handful of pluggable devices can handle the full range of wavelengths.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Wavelength-converting transponders originally translated the transmit wavelength of a client-layer signal into one of the DWDM system's internal wavelengths in the 1,550 nm band.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] External wavelengths in the 1,550 nm most likely need to be translated, as they almost certainly do not have the required frequency stability tolerances nor the optical power necessary for the system's EDFA.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] In the mid-1990s, however, wavelength-converting transponders rapidly took on the additional function of signal regeneration.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Signal regeneration in transponders quickly evolved through 1R to 2R to 3R and into overhead-monitoring multi-bitrate 3R regenerators.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] of the received optical signal, with little signal cleanup occurring.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] This limited the reach of early DWDM systems because the signal had to be handed off to a client-layer receiver (likely from a different vendor) before the signal deteriorated too far.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Signal monitoring was basically confined to optical domain parameters such as received power.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Some rudimentary signal-quality monitoring was done by such transmitters that basically looked at analogue parameters.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] 3R Transponders were fully digital and normally able to view SONET/SDH section layer overhead bytes such as A1 and A2 to determine signal quality health.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] transponders, which will normally mean the transponder is able to perform 3R regeneration on OC-3/12/48 signals, and possibly gigabit Ethernet, and reporting on signal health by monitoring SONET/SDH section layer overhead bytes.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Many transponders will be able to perform full multi-rate 3R in both directions.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] transponders, which will perform Section layer overhead monitoring to all rates up to and including OC-192.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] (from multiplexed transponder) has different names depending on vendor.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] It essentially performs some relatively simple time-division multiplexing of lower-rate signals into a higher-rate carrier within the system (a common example is the ability to accept 4 OC-48s and then output a single OC-192 in the 1,550 nm band).
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] For DWDM the range between C21-C60 is the most common range, for Mux/Demux in 8, 16, 40 or 96 sizes.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] As mentioned above, intermediate optical amplification sites in DWDM systems may allow for the dropping and adding of certain wavelength channels.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] In most systems deployed as of August 2006 this is done infrequently, because adding or dropping wavelengths requires manually inserting or replacing wavelength-selective cards.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] This is costly, and in some systems requires that all active traffic be removed from the DWDM system because inserting or removing the wavelength-specific cards interrupts the multi-wavelength optical signal.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] With a ROADM, network operators can remotely reconfigure the multiplexer by sending soft commands.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The architecture of the ROADM is such that dropping or adding wavelengths does not interrupt the *pass-through* channels.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Numerous technological approaches are utilized for various commercial ROADMs, the tradeoff being between cost, optical power, and flexibility.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] When the network topology is a mesh, where nodes are interconnected by fibers to form an arbitrary graph, an additional fiber interconnection device is needed to route the signals from an input port to the desired output port.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] These devices are called optical crossconnectors (OXCs).
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Various categories of OXCs include electronic ("opaque"), optical ("transparent"), and wavelength-selective devices.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Cisco's Enhanced WDM system is a network architecture that combines two different types of multiplexing technologies to transmit data over optical fibers.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] EWDM combines 1 Gbit/s Coarse Wave Division Multiplexing (CWDM) connections using SFPs and GBICs with 10 Gbit/s Dense Wave Division Multiplexing (DWDM) connections using XENPAK, X2 or XFP DWDM modules.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] The Enhanced WDM system can use either passive or boosted DWDM connections to allow a longer range for the connection.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] In addition to this, C form-factor pluggable modules deliver 100 Gbit/s Ethernet suitable for high-speed Internet backbone connections.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Shortwave WDM uses vertical-cavity surface-emitting laser (VCSEL) transceivers with four wavelengths in the 846 to 953 nm range over a single OM5 fiber, or two-fiber connectivity for OM3/OM4 fiber.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] ) communication, two wavelengths will be required if on the same fiber; if separate fibers are used in a so-called fiber pair, then the same wavelength is normally used and it is not WDM.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] As a result, at each end both a transmitter and a receiver will be required.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] A combination of a transmitter and a receiver is called a transceiver; it converts an electrical signal to and from an optical signal.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] WDM transceivers made for single-strand operation require the opposing transmitters to use different wavelengths.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] WDM transceivers additionally require an optical splitter/combiner to couple the transmitter and receiver paths onto the one fiber strand.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] In practice, the signal inputs and outputs will not be electrical but optical instead (typically at 1550 nm).
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] This means that in effect wavelength converters are needed instead, which is exactly what a transponder is.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] A transponder can be made up of two transceivers placed after each other: the first transceiver converting the 1550 nm optical signal to/from an electrical signal, and the second transceiver converting the electrical signal to/from an optical signal at the required wavelength.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] Transponders that don't use an intermediate electrical signal (all-optical transponders) are in development.
[src:passive-optical-network/wavelength-division-multiplexing] See also transponders (optical communications) for different functional views on the meaning of optical transponders.
